1
00:00:00,969 --> 00:00:03,338
<i>Previously on "Manhattan"...</i>

2
00:00:03,372 --> 00:00:06,610
- Music.
- That's right. Music.

3
00:00:06,644 --> 00:00:08,840
<i>Man: He's with her again.</i>

4
00:00:09,714 --> 00:00:12,484
We're gonna enjoy a
night to ourselves, hmm?

5
00:00:12,514 --> 00:00:14,379
And my husband won't even notice I'm out.

6
00:00:14,413 --> 00:00:15,940
We're WACs.

7
00:00:16,447 --> 00:00:18,115
Just transferred to the Hill.

8
00:00:18,149 --> 00:00:20,518
- (Both giggling)
- We were having fun.

9
00:00:20,553 --> 00:00:22,540
El, why won't you dance with me?

10
00:00:25,189 --> 00:00:27,927
The last three months, while you've been
making your name writing school papers

11
00:00:27,962 --> 00:00:29,601
and eating Cracker Jacks at Fenway,

12
00:00:29,636 --> 00:00:32,372
we've been stuck in this desert
shithole working six days a week.

13
00:00:32,756 --> 00:00:34,257
You just got a promotion.

14
00:00:34,282 --> 00:00:37,143
- It wouldn't kill you to smile.
- Can I think about it?

15
00:00:37,177 --> 00:00:38,481
There's a problem with Thin Man.

16
00:00:38,515 --> 00:00:41,382
- We're dead in the water.
- We are, too.

17
00:00:41,415 --> 00:00:43,415
So what are we gonna do about it?

18
00:00:46,370 --> 00:00:47,680
<i>(Knock on door)</i>

19
00:00:56,332 --> 00:00:57,902
Nearly midnight.

20
00:00:58,847 --> 00:01:01,205
People don't usually keep me waiting.

21
00:01:01,239 --> 00:01:04,144
I don't take an offer like
yours lightly, Dr. Akley.

22
00:01:04,178 --> 00:01:05,913
Well, it doesn't sound
like you take it at all.

23
00:01:05,947 --> 00:01:08,115
Charlie, since the day
you arrived in this desert,

24
00:01:08,150 --> 00:01:09,886
you've been rejecting my canteen.

25
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:12,390
Now I brought you to a
lake, you still won't drink.

26
00:01:12,424 --> 00:01:14,559
I've never taken it personally.

27
00:01:14,594 --> 00:01:16,446
I'm starting to wonder if maybe I should.

28
00:01:16,471 --> 00:01:17,654
I accept the job.

29
00:01:25,547 --> 00:01:27,082
I'll pour us another.

30
00:01:27,117 --> 00:01:29,286
<i>-  But I have some conditions.
- (Chuckles)</i>

31
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:31,990
Three to be exact.

32
00:01:32,024 --> 00:01:34,060
Otherwise, I can't be your deputy.

33
00:01:34,094 --> 00:01:35,964
What are your conditions?

34
00:01:36,523 --> 00:01:38,504
Security is slipshod.

35
00:01:38,539 --> 00:01:40,606
I want to bolster compartmentalization.

36
00:01:40,641 --> 00:01:43,243
Make information
strictly need-to-know.

37
00:01:43,278 --> 00:01:45,539
I'll take it under consideration.

38
00:01:46,154 --> 00:01:48,740
What else do I need to know?

39
00:01:48,765 --> 00:01:52,669
We need to thoroughly rattle-test all
our work down to the last data point.

40
00:01:52,694 --> 00:01:53,770
Check all the math...

41
00:01:53,795 --> 00:01:56,262
We're through the design phase.
You make these boys backtrack,

42
00:01:56,296 --> 00:01:57,896
they will hang you by your slide rule.

43
00:01:57,931 --> 00:02:00,567
To be frank, sir, I've seen more than a few

44
00:02:00,601 --> 00:02:03,311
sloppy calculations come
across my desk recently.

45
00:02:03,444 --> 00:02:05,504
If Thin Man were assembled
based on faulty numbers,

46
00:02:05,538 --> 00:02:07,273
it'd be a hell of a black eye.

47
00:02:10,144 --> 00:02:11,904
Your funeral.

48
00:02:13,615 --> 00:02:15,516
What's your third condition?

49
00:02:15,551 --> 00:02:17,751
<i>Fritz: More detonators won't
change the laws of physics.</i>

50
00:02:17,786 --> 00:02:20,288
Well, we never let the laws of
physics get in our way before.

51
00:02:20,322 --> 00:02:22,291
We checked the Brit's math a hundred times.

52
00:02:22,326 --> 00:02:24,012
It says that the only
problem with implosion

53
00:02:24,037 --> 00:02:25,361
is that it's completely impossible.

54
00:02:25,395 --> 00:02:27,159
<i>I try to keep a positive attitude...</i>

55
00:02:27,184 --> 00:02:29,798
- Full speed ahead.
- Towards what destination?

56
00:02:29,833 --> 00:02:32,401
Have a little faith in
Frank. He got us this far.

57
00:02:32,435 --> 00:02:34,366
It has been a group effort, tulip.

58
00:02:36,606 --> 00:02:39,609
- Helen Prins.
- Yes.

59
00:02:39,644 --> 00:02:41,878
Gather your personal items, ma'am.

60
00:03:11,985 --> 00:03:16,848
<i>(Playing on car radio) ♪ Ten
more miles down the road ♪</i>

61
00:03:17,423 --> 00:03:20,855
<i>♪ Ten more miles down the road ♪</i>

62
00:03:21,759 --> 00:03:26,433
<i>♪ My heart is heavy,
Lord knows I'm weary ♪</i>

63
00:03:26,468 --> 00:03:30,356
<i>♪ Ten more miles down the road ♪</i>

64
00:03:31,239 --> 00:03:35,354
<i>♪ Ten more miles down the line ♪</i>

65
00:03:36,006 --> 00:03:39,556
<i>♪ Ten more miles and she'll be mine ♪</i>

66
00:03:40,079 --> 00:03:43,181
<i>♪ Then we'll start living, forget... ♪</i>

67
00:03:52,602 --> 00:03:54,374
Hello?

68
00:04:00,898 --> 00:04:02,597
Anybody home?

69
00:04:09,738 --> 00:04:11,439
(Knocks)

70
00:04:15,647 --> 00:04:17,267
<i>Frank: Hello?</i>

71
00:04:21,489 --> 00:04:23,424
<i>(Explosion in distance)</i>

72
00:04:25,761 --> 00:04:30,864
♪ She's waiting for me and I know... ♪

73
00:04:30,898 --> 00:04:32,532
Hello there.

74
00:04:32,566 --> 00:04:34,300
You're Lazar, yeah?

75
00:04:34,335 --> 00:04:36,436
I'm Frank Winter.

76
00:04:36,471 --> 00:04:39,674
- (Mumbles, chuckles)
- Hell of a backyard you got here.

77
00:04:39,708 --> 00:04:41,911
Must be the only place on the Hill

78
00:04:41,945 --> 00:04:44,009
where you can't see a fence.

79
00:04:44,851 --> 00:04:46,517
(Chuckles)

80
00:04:46,552 --> 00:04:48,018
One more.

81
00:04:48,053 --> 00:04:49,995
39, 40.

82
00:04:50,020 --> 00:04:52,658
40. 44.

83
00:04:59,370 --> 00:05:00,974
Sure hope that's one of ours.

84
00:05:01,008 --> 00:05:02,539
<i>(Jet engine roaring)</i>

85
00:05:02,574 --> 00:05:06,641
One, two, three, four...

86
00:05:06,676 --> 00:05:11,280
five, six, seven.

87
00:05:11,314 --> 00:05:14,048
Why are they always late?

88
00:05:22,153 --> 00:05:23,186
Good!

89
00:05:23,221 --> 00:05:26,820
<i>(Theme music playing)</i>

90
00:05:49,953 --> 00:05:52,261
Manhattan 1x09
Spooky Action at a Distance

91
00:05:53,423 --> 00:05:57,684
Sync and corrections by Albanda
www.Addic7ed.com

92
00:05:59,619 --> 00:06:01,861
I brought you a bottle of vodka.

93
00:06:01,886 --> 00:06:03,549
Heard you make your own sausages.

94
00:06:03,612 --> 00:06:05,361
Thought you might be interested in a trade.

95
00:06:05,386 --> 00:06:09,516
- Sausage?
- Yeah, my wife, she just loves them.

96
00:06:09,541 --> 00:06:12,108
Uh-huh. That's not why you're here.

97
00:06:12,492 --> 00:06:15,066
- Sorry?
- I said that's not why you're here.

98
00:06:15,091 --> 00:06:18,865
I know you. I know that your
group is in the dog shed.

99
00:06:18,890 --> 00:06:22,295
No more explosives. No more detonators.

100
00:06:22,873 --> 00:06:25,675
You probably won't even get matches

101
00:06:25,709 --> 00:06:27,398
to light your cigarettes.

102
00:06:27,848 --> 00:06:30,386
So you come to my armory

103
00:06:30,582 --> 00:06:33,519
and you ask me for some sausage?

104
00:06:35,617 --> 00:06:38,985
I hate liars. I hate vodka.

105
00:06:39,325 --> 00:06:42,161
I thought this stuff was
mother's milk in Moscow.

106
00:06:42,195 --> 00:06:43,905
I'm not Russian.

107
00:06:43,930 --> 00:06:45,386
I'm American.

108
00:06:47,551 --> 00:06:49,586
<i>Now get off my property!</i>

109
00:07:00,107 --> 00:07:03,284
Gentleman, as we approach the finish line,

110
00:07:03,309 --> 00:07:06,412
I will be stepping back from day-to-day
operations around this office.

111
00:07:06,437 --> 00:07:08,740
However, you will not be without a leader.

112
00:07:09,089 --> 00:07:10,784
As of this afternoon,

113
00:07:11,126 --> 00:07:13,026
you will report to Charlie Isaacs.

114
00:07:13,238 --> 00:07:14,872
(Applause)

115
00:07:17,292 --> 00:07:19,728
This room contains some of the finest

116
00:07:19,762 --> 00:07:21,764
scientific minds in, um...

117
00:07:23,501 --> 00:07:25,071
well, in New Mexico.

118
00:07:25,106 --> 00:07:27,640
<i>As I take over, I'm going
to be asking a lot of you.</i>

119
00:07:27,674 --> 00:07:30,842
Not just your hard work and brilliance,

120
00:07:30,876 --> 00:07:32,602
but also your loyalty.

121
00:07:33,914 --> 00:07:36,620
To me and my new deputy.

122
00:07:38,422 --> 00:07:40,964
If anyone has a problem
answering to a woman,

123
00:07:41,863 --> 00:07:44,289
I can arrange for transfer to another site.

124
00:07:50,672 --> 00:07:53,777
<i>Helen: Frank! Where have you been?</i>

125
00:07:53,811 --> 00:07:56,113
Did you hear what Akley
did, that smug prick?

126
00:07:56,148 --> 00:07:59,174
Heard he gave you a promotion.
Congratulations. Why aren't you in there?

127
00:07:59,199 --> 00:08:01,422
Well, they're not even letting
me into their offices yet.

128
00:08:01,456 --> 00:08:04,725
Or in ours. They're making me take
another ridiculous polygraph test again.

129
00:08:04,759 --> 00:08:06,661
- You'll pass it.
- I don't want to pass it.

130
00:08:06,695 --> 00:08:08,331
It's for the best, Helen.

131
00:08:08,365 --> 00:08:11,199
Implosion's the endgame, Frank.
I want to be a part of it.

132
00:08:11,234 --> 00:08:14,571
- Tell Akley he can't have me.
- I can't do that.

133
00:08:14,606 --> 00:08:15,676
Please, Frank.

134
00:08:15,701 --> 00:08:17,766
It was my idea to transfer
you in the first place.

135
00:08:18,814 --> 00:08:20,081
What?

136
00:08:20,428 --> 00:08:21,716
Why?

137
00:08:21,750 --> 00:08:25,066
Akley has a room full of
IBM machines he doesn't need.

138
00:08:25,550 --> 00:08:27,684
You traded me for a calculator?

139
00:08:27,718 --> 00:08:30,087
I did what I had to do for
the good of the project.

140
00:08:32,023 --> 00:08:33,957
When everybody else
was ready to pack it in,

141
00:08:33,992 --> 00:08:36,293
I never wavered, Frank.

142
00:08:37,314 --> 00:08:39,663
You really are a son of a bitch.

143
00:08:42,269 --> 00:08:44,137
Elodie: Lunch break?

144
00:08:47,155 --> 00:08:49,045
I brought my own sandwich.

145
00:08:49,079 --> 00:08:51,380
No, this one is better. Saucisson.

146
00:08:54,652 --> 00:08:56,329
It's one thing you avoid me

147
00:08:56,354 --> 00:08:58,338
and now you refuse even to break bread?

148
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:00,928
Very rude.

149
00:09:00,953 --> 00:09:02,588
I'm not avoiding you.

150
00:09:03,930 --> 00:09:06,599
Well, at least have a drink.

151
00:09:07,038 --> 00:09:09,537
Need to wash down all
those Yiddish consonants.

152
00:09:15,035 --> 00:09:17,439
You worried I'm gonna slip you a Mickey?

153
00:09:18,984 --> 00:09:20,948
(Laughs)

154
00:09:25,954 --> 00:09:27,553
Ahh.

155
00:09:29,222 --> 00:09:32,058
Neonatal seborrheic dermatitis

156
00:09:32,092 --> 00:09:33,994
is a not uncommon condition

157
00:09:34,028 --> 00:09:37,396
presenting as yellowish, crusty
scales on the infant's scalp.

158
00:09:37,431 --> 00:09:41,099
If you observe this in your
newborn, ladies, do not panic.

159
00:09:41,134 --> 00:09:43,670
Treatments include, but
are not limited to...

160
00:09:43,704 --> 00:09:45,572
Dr. Adelman, bed seven is crowning.

161
00:09:45,606 --> 00:09:47,606
If you'll excuse me.

162
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:50,041
Ladies, I'm gonna leave
you with Mrs. Winter.

163
00:09:50,075 --> 00:09:52,343
A wonderful new addition to our team.

164
00:09:52,377 --> 00:09:54,179
She'll distribute everything you need.

165
00:09:54,213 --> 00:09:55,614
When in doubt, just remember,

166
00:09:55,649 --> 00:09:58,485
mothers have been doing this for millennia.

167
00:09:58,840 --> 00:10:02,156
If cavewomen could do it, you can, too.

168
00:10:05,127 --> 00:10:08,634
So, um... compliments of the hospital.

169
00:10:08,668 --> 00:10:11,137
Please, help yourselves.

170
00:10:19,013 --> 00:10:20,681
<i>(Explosion)</i>

171
00:10:22,281 --> 00:10:24,648
<i>(Baby crying)</i>

172
00:10:31,293 --> 00:10:32,895
<i>(Explosion)</i>

173
00:10:39,298 --> 00:10:41,668
Anybody home?

174
00:10:47,010 --> 00:10:49,577
- Hi.
- Hi.

175
00:10:50,356 --> 00:10:53,114
Javier wanted to talk to you.

176
00:10:53,149 --> 00:10:55,650
Javier, who is he?

177
00:10:55,685 --> 00:10:57,686
Paloma's cousin.

178
00:11:10,801 --> 00:11:12,993
He's been waiting an hour.

179
00:11:13,636 --> 00:11:16,107
(Speaking Spanish)

180
00:11:19,478 --> 00:11:22,178
He says, "It's been hard at the pueblo."

181
00:11:22,212 --> 00:11:25,081
<i>(Javier speaking Spanish)</i>

182
00:11:25,116 --> 00:11:27,285
"The farm, the harvest was bad this year."

183
00:11:27,319 --> 00:11:30,286
<i>(Javier speaking Spanish)</i>

184
00:11:38,657 --> 00:11:40,692
"Paloma has so many skills."

185
00:11:40,726 --> 00:11:43,722
<i>- (Javier speaks Spanish)
-  "Talents."</i>

186
00:11:44,275 --> 00:11:47,111
<i>And we appreciated what she had to offer.</i>

187
00:11:47,848 --> 00:11:50,048
<i>(Javier speaking Spanish)</i>

188
00:11:50,865 --> 00:11:53,931
<i>Paloma told him you're a generous man.</i>

189
00:11:53,965 --> 00:11:55,434
What does he want?

190
00:11:55,542 --> 00:11:57,606
(Speaks Spanish)

191
00:11:58,678 --> 00:11:59,791
"A truck."

192
00:11:59,816 --> 00:12:02,417
<i>- A what?
-  He wants a pickup truck.</i>

193
00:12:07,445 --> 00:12:08,898
A pickup truck?

194
00:12:09,256 --> 00:12:11,111
(Speaks Spanish)

195
00:12:12,617 --> 00:12:14,687
<i>Callie: I think he needs it by Friday.</i>

196
00:12:16,624 --> 00:12:18,011
Well...

197
00:12:19,124 --> 00:12:21,462
I'll see what we have lying around.

198
00:12:27,401 --> 00:12:30,402
<i>-  Adios.
-  Gracias por la leche.</i>

199
00:12:42,036 --> 00:12:44,906
Man: Have you ever inflicted
physical harm on others?

200
00:12:45,479 --> 00:12:47,091
No. Jesus.

201
00:12:48,613 --> 00:12:52,720
Have you ever inflicted
physical harm on yourself?

202
00:12:53,419 --> 00:12:56,087
Well, I drink too much.

203
00:12:56,122 --> 00:13:00,024
Are you now or have you ever been
a member of the Communist Party?

204
00:13:00,058 --> 00:13:02,930
Yes. Joe Stalin and I are pen pals.

205
00:13:06,401 --> 00:13:08,365
No, I'm not a Communist.

206
00:13:08,399 --> 00:13:09,977
Do you believe in God?

207
00:13:10,399 --> 00:13:12,201
I met him. His name's Niels Bohr.

208
00:13:12,236 --> 00:13:14,137
This is not a vaudeville routine.

209
00:13:14,172 --> 00:13:16,038
I was asked these questions before

210
00:13:16,072 --> 00:13:18,073
and my answers were the same as now.

211
00:13:18,107 --> 00:13:19,710
If you'd like, I could have a smoke

212
00:13:19,745 --> 00:13:21,178
and you could copy my old form.

213
00:13:21,213 --> 00:13:23,445
Have you in the past or do you plan now

214
00:13:23,479 --> 00:13:26,181
to pass intelligence to the
government of occupied Holland?

215
00:13:26,215 --> 00:13:27,334
Nope.

216
00:13:27,359 --> 00:13:29,292
Have you in the past or do you plan now

217
00:13:29,317 --> 00:13:32,719
to pass intelligence between
divisions of this installation?

218
00:13:33,822 --> 00:13:35,589
No.

219
00:13:43,269 --> 00:13:44,772
<i>Announcer: Your attention, please.</i>

220
00:13:44,806 --> 00:13:47,309
<i>Be advised, due to tight
security on the Hill,</i>

221
00:13:47,343 --> 00:13:50,215
<i>all residents are subject
to random searches.</i>

222
00:13:58,343 --> 00:14:01,042
<i>- Soldier: Next.
- What's the holdup?</i>

223
00:14:01,421 --> 00:14:03,388
You should know. Your orders.

224
00:14:03,423 --> 00:14:05,993
Extra security was supposed to
be internal for our purposes.

225
00:14:06,028 --> 00:14:08,966
Oh, it's internal, all
right. Checking every orifice.

226
00:14:09,001 --> 00:14:10,935
<i>Man: Please, open your briefcase.</i>

227
00:14:10,970 --> 00:14:13,505
<i>ID's out.</i>

228
00:14:16,009 --> 00:14:17,745
<i>Next.</i>

229
00:14:20,051 --> 00:14:23,049
All I'm saying is the boys
need direction. They're idling.

230
00:14:23,857 --> 00:14:26,026
They wanna go to work for Helen?

231
00:14:26,060 --> 00:14:28,726
Maybe we all have to consider options.

232
00:14:28,760 --> 00:14:32,297
We have thrown everything we know
at it and a few things we don't.

233
00:14:32,322 --> 00:14:35,022
Density maximization, activated charcoal.

234
00:14:35,265 --> 00:14:37,920
None of it can overcome
the shock wave problem.

235
00:14:38,068 --> 00:14:40,704
Oppenheimer wanted to shut
us down before the Brits.

236
00:14:40,738 --> 00:14:42,741
Now it's just a matter of when.

237
00:14:45,009 --> 00:14:47,011
If we have to join forces with Akley...

238
00:14:48,314 --> 00:14:49,947
that's what we'll do.

239
00:15:21,483 --> 00:15:25,354
<i>(Clock ticking)</i>

240
00:16:00,586 --> 00:16:03,789
<i>Callie: Why doesn't Paloma
just come back and work for us?</i>

241
00:16:03,824 --> 00:16:06,111
We're doing just fine without a maid.

242
00:16:07,260 --> 00:16:09,610
They cost too much anyway.

243
00:16:10,660 --> 00:16:13,511
A pickup costs a lot more.

244
00:16:13,998 --> 00:16:15,565
And yet you're considering that.

245
00:16:15,600 --> 00:16:17,535
You know, this isn't
your problem, young lady.

246
00:16:17,569 --> 00:16:19,137
It's not Mom's problem either?

247
00:16:22,109 --> 00:16:25,516
You didn't see how upset she
got at that Indian funeral.

248
00:16:26,919 --> 00:16:31,023
It was just too much like it used to be.

249
00:16:32,822 --> 00:16:35,358
Let's let her enjoy the new job, okay?

250
00:16:36,996 --> 00:16:38,763
Okay.

251
00:16:41,899 --> 00:16:44,014
Why don't we lock our doors, by the way?

252
00:16:44,039 --> 00:16:45,672
What do you mean?

253
00:16:45,900 --> 00:16:48,167
When I let Javier out,

254
00:16:48,201 --> 00:16:50,737
he said that people
should lock their doors.

255
00:16:54,227 --> 00:16:56,595
<i>-  (Pounds on window)
- Wait.</i>

256
00:16:58,780 --> 00:17:00,612
Stay there.

257
00:17:07,624 --> 00:17:09,740
What the hell are you doing here?

258
00:17:11,083 --> 00:17:12,694
We need to talk.

259
00:17:14,564 --> 00:17:16,298
Be right back.

260
00:17:18,867 --> 00:17:22,238
MPs are sweeping my office,
they're frisking everyone.

261
00:17:22,272 --> 00:17:24,140
- We've created a monster.
- A useful monster.

262
00:17:24,175 --> 00:17:25,978
You remember, you knocked on my door.

263
00:17:26,012 --> 00:17:28,171
And now 50 of my guys are
working on your problem.

264
00:17:28,171 --> 00:17:29,217
Our problem.

265
00:17:29,283 --> 00:17:32,351
I'm in a henhouse full of
foxes who think they're hens.

266
00:17:32,385 --> 00:17:34,420
Have you told them you had to
recheck all the Thin Man math?

267
00:17:34,445 --> 00:17:35,533
- Yeah.
- Then

268
00:17:35,558 --> 00:17:37,023
I don't understand, what's the issue?

269
00:17:37,057 --> 00:17:38,856
These are some of the
smartest guys in the world.

270
00:17:38,890 --> 00:17:40,557
How long do you think it'll take for them

271
00:17:40,591 --> 00:17:42,159
to realize they're working on implosion?

272
00:17:42,194 --> 00:17:45,160
The shock wave calculations
are broken up into tiny parts.

273
00:17:45,548 --> 00:17:47,347
If the puzzle pieces are small enough,

274
00:17:47,372 --> 00:17:49,639
there is no way one guy
can see the big picture.

275
00:17:49,664 --> 00:17:51,665
Not one of your guys anyway.

276
00:17:51,837 --> 00:17:55,209
I want you to requisition 12 sets
of detonators and 100 pounds of TNT.

277
00:17:55,234 --> 00:17:57,916
No, I get you the math, you worry
about experiments. That's the deal.

278
00:17:57,941 --> 00:17:59,145
Well, there's a new deal.

279
00:17:59,301 --> 00:18:01,638
Akley gave you full authority
to sign for resources.

280
00:18:01,663 --> 00:18:03,696
Thin Man is finished
with explosives testing.

281
00:18:03,721 --> 00:18:05,754
I go asking for detonators and TNT,

282
00:18:05,779 --> 00:18:08,114
the army will be on my
doorstep an hour later.

283
00:18:08,419 --> 00:18:09,755
My source won't give us any.

284
00:18:09,790 --> 00:18:11,906
This was your idea, figure it out.

285
00:18:12,529 --> 00:18:13,929
I need you to leave now.

286
00:18:13,954 --> 00:18:16,355
Don't you come back to this house again.

287
00:18:37,222 --> 00:18:39,056
(Knocks)

288
00:18:42,561 --> 00:18:44,793
You were right, I lied.

289
00:18:44,828 --> 00:18:47,296
If you know who I am, then you
know I've spent the last year

290
00:18:47,330 --> 00:18:49,432
working on implosion.

291
00:18:49,466 --> 00:18:52,335
I'm not ready to give up on it.

292
00:18:52,369 --> 00:18:55,204
No matter what the army
or anyone else says.

293
00:18:57,073 --> 00:18:58,473
I respect that.

294
00:18:58,507 --> 00:19:00,774
I need detonators. I need TNT.

295
00:19:00,807 --> 00:19:04,875
Explosives belongs to your army.

296
00:19:04,909 --> 00:19:06,776
Yeah, but you're in
charge of doling them out.

297
00:19:06,810 --> 00:19:10,460
Should I go to the colonel and tell
him you're going behind his back, huh?

298
00:19:10,828 --> 00:19:12,473
You won't do that.

299
00:19:13,696 --> 00:19:14,917
You don't know me.

300
00:19:14,951 --> 00:19:17,486
I know you worked at the Navy
Ordnance Bureau last year.

301
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:20,626
- (Scoffs)
- I made some calls this morning.

302
00:19:20,660 --> 00:19:23,627
- Asked an old friend there about you.
- Who?

303
00:19:23,662 --> 00:19:25,028
Albert Einstein.

304
00:19:26,364 --> 00:19:28,889
He told me you were a good scientist.

305
00:19:29,533 --> 00:19:31,433
He also told me you could be trusted.

306
00:19:31,468 --> 00:19:35,169
Listen, the only risk I would like to take

307
00:19:35,204 --> 00:19:37,339
is to work with my explosives.

308
00:19:38,107 --> 00:19:39,889
Understand?

309
00:19:42,281 --> 00:19:44,165
Fair enough.

310
00:19:45,484 --> 00:19:47,086
For your time.

311
00:19:47,801 --> 00:19:49,918
I don't take bribes.

312
00:19:51,787 --> 00:19:53,688
And Einstein was wrong.

313
00:19:54,237 --> 00:19:57,144
I'm not a scientist, I'm an engineer.

314
00:20:07,679 --> 00:20:11,018
All right, stay where
Mommy can see you, Joey.

315
00:20:13,086 --> 00:20:15,888
To him, this is completely normal, hmm?

316
00:20:17,725 --> 00:20:21,432
Then again, who am I to say what is normal?

317
00:20:27,741 --> 00:20:29,377
(Giggles)

318
00:20:33,301 --> 00:20:35,067
(Sighs)

319
00:20:43,763 --> 00:20:46,075
- Was it normal?
- Hmm?

320
00:20:46,732 --> 00:20:48,934
What happened between us that night.

321
00:20:52,031 --> 00:20:54,258
You Americans.

322
00:20:55,072 --> 00:20:58,066
Always looking for explanations.

323
00:20:59,110 --> 00:21:00,564
Or penance.

324
00:21:02,076 --> 00:21:03,877
What do you think happened?

325
00:21:03,912 --> 00:21:05,680
You fell asleep.

326
00:21:05,715 --> 00:21:07,214
(Giggles)

327
00:21:07,248 --> 00:21:09,764
Yes, but before I fell asleep.

328
00:21:10,766 --> 00:21:14,395
You know, the first time I made
love was a day just like this.

329
00:21:14,666 --> 00:21:17,164
Spring in winter.

330
00:21:18,165 --> 00:21:20,365
His name was Philippe.

331
00:21:21,399 --> 00:21:23,400
He had this belt...

332
00:21:23,435 --> 00:21:26,302
leather, all beat up.

333
00:21:28,467 --> 00:21:30,835
When he moved to London for university,

334
00:21:30,869 --> 00:21:32,804
I made him give the belt to me.

335
00:21:34,373 --> 00:21:35,807
Still have it.

336
00:21:35,841 --> 00:21:38,510
Every now and then, I take it out.

337
00:21:39,577 --> 00:21:41,378
Sometimes I even...

338
00:21:41,843 --> 00:21:44,847
bite it and taste it.

339
00:21:47,691 --> 00:21:50,259
Suddenly, I'm right back there.

340
00:21:53,262 --> 00:21:55,763
What if your husband found it?

341
00:21:57,432 --> 00:22:00,767
<i>Secrets are what keep us alive, chérie.</i>

342
00:22:02,841 --> 00:22:06,745
Without them, we'd just be normal.

343
00:22:13,018 --> 00:22:14,652
(Sighs)

344
00:22:21,862 --> 00:22:23,866
Well, come right in.

345
00:22:23,891 --> 00:22:26,629
If I'm going to be your number
two, you better get used to it.

346
00:22:27,235 --> 00:22:28,635
Are you ready to start working?

347
00:22:28,669 --> 00:22:31,707
You mean keep working
on implosion for Frank?

348
00:22:36,409 --> 00:22:38,199
Keep your voice down.

349
00:22:41,755 --> 00:22:44,793
- He told you?
- He didn't have to. I'm a clever girl.

350
00:22:44,827 --> 00:22:47,062
Thin Man has the
resources, but it's flawed.

351
00:22:47,096 --> 00:22:49,131
Implosion's the right model,
but we have no manpower.

352
00:22:49,165 --> 00:22:50,843
What you guys can do in
a day will take us 10.

353
00:22:50,868 --> 00:22:52,035
I had to keep you in the dark.

354
00:22:52,069 --> 00:22:53,903
- Or I wouldn't pass the polygraph.
- Right.

355
00:22:53,938 --> 00:22:55,279
Right.

356
00:22:55,569 --> 00:22:56,999
So now I'm complicit in your crime.

357
00:22:57,024 --> 00:22:59,322
We're all sticking our necks
out here. We don't have a choice.

358
00:22:59,347 --> 00:23:01,147
I always have a choice.

359
00:23:03,456 --> 00:23:05,087
You can't tell anyone about this.

360
00:23:07,039 --> 00:23:10,671
By the way, I'm screwing Paul Crosley.

361
00:23:17,067 --> 00:23:19,735
<i>Meeks: Terrible things
always happen in threes.</i>

362
00:23:19,770 --> 00:23:22,404
Next, they'll probably
stop printing "Superman."

363
00:23:22,438 --> 00:23:25,076
<i>- Helen will find her way back somehow.
- Crosley: I say good riddance.</i>

364
00:23:25,110 --> 00:23:27,246
She doesn't know anything
about shock waves anyway.

365
00:23:33,992 --> 00:23:35,633
We need to have some fun, boys.

366
00:23:35,658 --> 00:23:38,030
Should we assay your urine again?

367
00:23:39,528 --> 00:23:41,597
(Grunts)

368
00:23:41,631 --> 00:23:43,601
(Chuckles)

369
00:23:46,354 --> 00:23:48,257
Psilocybe cubensis.

370
00:23:48,282 --> 00:23:50,314
Welcome to the wingding, gentlemen.

371
00:23:51,442 --> 00:23:53,607
- Mushrooms?
- Psychotropic mushrooms.

372
00:23:54,011 --> 00:23:55,861
Got 'em at the WAC dorm.

373
00:23:55,886 --> 00:23:58,019
One of Jeannie's clients paid with these.

374
00:23:58,044 --> 00:23:59,544
Oh, Jeannie's still seeing clients.

375
00:23:59,776 --> 00:24:01,876
<i>Fritz: They're from the natives.</i>

376
00:24:01,910 --> 00:24:05,450
We scarf these down,
you'll see quite a show.

377
00:24:05,484 --> 00:24:06,785
<i>Meeks: Mm.</i>

378
00:24:06,820 --> 00:24:08,818
It's better than diddling
our thumbs in the lab.

379
00:24:08,852 --> 00:24:11,552
You twiddle thumbs, you diddle yourself.

380
00:24:11,586 --> 00:24:13,154
Frequently, I'm sure.

381
00:24:13,734 --> 00:24:17,034
Uh, you know, I tried marijuana once,

382
00:24:17,059 --> 00:24:18,694
you don't even want to know what happened.

383
00:24:18,719 --> 00:24:20,512
Let me guess, you forgot
your mother's phone number?

384
00:24:20,537 --> 00:24:23,664
Come on. The Indians have been eating
these for centuries. You will be fine.

385
00:24:23,698 --> 00:24:24,876
Nah.

386
00:24:25,565 --> 00:24:29,258
Meeks. Meeks. Meeks.

387
00:24:29,283 --> 00:24:31,751
(Chanting Meeks)

388
00:24:44,180 --> 00:24:46,448
(Both cheer)

389
00:24:46,482 --> 00:24:49,211
- Are you satisfied?
- See you in Wonderland.

390
00:24:49,951 --> 00:24:51,952
<i>(Music playing)</i>

391
00:24:54,123 --> 00:24:56,291
<i>Elodie: Oh, no!</i>

392
00:24:56,325 --> 00:24:59,294
<i>No, no. She's way too wholesome.</i>

393
00:24:59,328 --> 00:25:01,331
- What?
- All those high-neck blouses.

394
00:25:01,356 --> 00:25:02,956
No, but she's so beautiful

395
00:25:02,981 --> 00:25:05,149
and she's married to Laurence Olivier.

396
00:25:05,174 --> 00:25:06,607
He can have her.

397
00:25:06,632 --> 00:25:10,434
I would take the sweater girl
over Vivien Leigh every night.

398
00:25:10,772 --> 00:25:13,773
- "Sweater girl"?
- Lana Turner.

399
00:25:13,807 --> 00:25:15,845
Oh, she wears

400
00:25:15,879 --> 00:25:18,915
the most beautiful sweaters

401
00:25:18,949 --> 00:25:21,616
- on a pretty little figure like yours.
- Oh!

402
00:25:37,289 --> 00:25:39,391
Mm. It's getting late.

403
00:25:39,644 --> 00:25:41,577
Oh, keep your maid another hour.

404
00:25:41,612 --> 00:25:43,579
- It costs pennies.
- I really should get back.

405
00:25:45,887 --> 00:25:48,424
You think too much about "should."

406
00:25:53,913 --> 00:25:56,441
Look at that, home before dinner.

407
00:25:57,694 --> 00:26:00,965
- Oh, Mrs. Isaacs, hello.
- Hello.

408
00:26:02,032 --> 00:26:05,549
I was just on my way. Charlie
should be back any time now.

409
00:26:05,574 --> 00:26:08,111
Well, it looked to me

410
00:26:08,136 --> 00:26:11,637
like he'd be there half the night.

411
00:26:12,155 --> 00:26:14,722
<i>Heavy's the head that wears the crown.</i>

412
00:26:14,757 --> 00:26:16,123
Mm.

413
00:26:16,625 --> 00:26:18,458
Won't you stay for dinner?

414
00:26:18,492 --> 00:26:21,462
- I really shouldn't.
- Yes, stay.

415
00:26:21,496 --> 00:26:25,262
Why go home and wait for your man
when you can be waited on for a change?

416
00:26:34,535 --> 00:26:36,371
So this is nirvana?

417
00:26:37,214 --> 00:26:40,117
Yeah, your fungi weren't much fun, Fritz.

418
00:26:40,510 --> 00:26:42,316
Fungi.

419
00:26:42,908 --> 00:26:45,777
Funicular, funambulist,

420
00:26:45,812 --> 00:26:48,179
funkiness, funnel cake.

421
00:26:49,748 --> 00:26:51,749
(Both laughing)

422
00:26:56,822 --> 00:26:58,923
Waste of a perfectly good evening.

423
00:26:58,957 --> 00:27:00,725
I'm going to run my lines with Phyllis.

424
00:27:00,760 --> 00:27:02,762
(Laughing continues)

425
00:27:10,074 --> 00:27:11,508
(Grunts)

426
00:27:12,943 --> 00:27:14,677
(Bleating)

427
00:27:17,647 --> 00:27:20,954
- Can you see them?
- Yes, I also see a moat and boat.

428
00:27:20,989 --> 00:27:23,123
And I am sailing towards an asymptote.

429
00:27:24,625 --> 00:27:27,394
I knew we were starting to
understand each other, Fritz.

430
00:27:30,199 --> 00:27:32,801
Soldier: Guess it's too much drink.

431
00:27:38,705 --> 00:27:40,205
Thanks.

432
00:27:55,678 --> 00:27:57,711
You're in love with Helen, aren't you?

433
00:28:01,039 --> 00:28:02,539
Yeah, I suppose I am.

434
00:28:04,694 --> 00:28:07,495
That's great. That's so great.

435
00:28:08,918 --> 00:28:10,385
That's great.

436
00:28:13,670 --> 00:28:15,069
Be careful.

437
00:28:35,246 --> 00:28:37,115
<i>(Door opens)</i>

438
00:28:37,224 --> 00:28:38,224
Frank.

439
00:28:38,703 --> 00:28:41,875
<i>- Liza: What's that?
- It's a radio.</i>

440
00:28:43,571 --> 00:28:45,942
But we already have a radio.

441
00:28:46,503 --> 00:28:48,338
It's for Callie.

442
00:28:56,492 --> 00:28:58,428
<i>Guard: Come forward, please.</i>

443
00:28:58,462 --> 00:29:00,232
Open that briefcase.

444
00:29:00,266 --> 00:29:01,733
- (Laughing)
- Stop.

445
00:29:01,767 --> 00:29:03,033
<i>Guard: Have your ID's out.</i>

446
00:29:03,068 --> 00:29:06,421
Hey, am I acting normal?

447
00:29:07,307 --> 00:29:09,371
Just make sure we all
smile big at the brass.

448
00:29:09,406 --> 00:29:12,508
- They won't suspect a thing.
- Okay, stop it. Stop being weird.

449
00:29:14,411 --> 00:29:17,746
Meeks, you need to eat some more.

450
00:29:17,780 --> 00:29:19,982
Maybe your metabolism's different.

451
00:29:20,016 --> 00:29:22,217
Rate of absorption's too low.

452
00:29:23,554 --> 00:29:25,450
What did you just say?

453
00:29:25,962 --> 00:29:27,962
I said I think you need to eat some more.

454
00:29:27,987 --> 00:29:30,157
No, "metabolism."

455
00:29:30,182 --> 00:29:32,050
Rates of absorption.

456
00:29:32,227 --> 00:29:34,360
Uh, did you cross-check

457
00:29:34,394 --> 00:29:37,493
the Pu-239 absorption rate
against your old tamper charts?

458
00:29:37,528 --> 00:29:38,794
- What?
- Huh?

459
00:29:38,829 --> 00:29:40,295
- Did you?
- No, of course not.

460
00:29:40,330 --> 00:29:41,903
The model changed.

461
00:29:41,928 --> 00:29:43,661
(Gasping)

462
00:29:43,799 --> 00:29:46,399
It was right in front of us.

463
00:29:46,434 --> 00:29:48,400
- All along.
- Yeah.

464
00:29:48,435 --> 00:29:50,300
<i>- Man: Next.
- We have to go back.</i>

465
00:29:50,334 --> 00:29:52,034
Hey. Hey, hey, hey, hey.

466
00:29:52,068 --> 00:29:53,936
Hey, hey, hey. Hey.

467
00:29:53,970 --> 00:29:57,338
Pull it together.

468
00:29:58,142 --> 00:30:00,007
We have work to do.

469
00:30:00,041 --> 00:30:01,642
Come on.

470
00:30:07,346 --> 00:30:10,315
<i>(Music playing)</i>

471
00:30:15,219 --> 00:30:18,333
Elodie loves Josephine Baker.

472
00:30:18,358 --> 00:30:20,276
- Ooh.
- But I think she

473
00:30:20,301 --> 00:30:22,833
couldn't cut it in the States,

474
00:30:22,867 --> 00:30:26,003
so she hops across the pond

475
00:30:26,037 --> 00:30:28,635
and kisses the frogs.

476
00:30:29,542 --> 00:30:31,110
<i>(Music playing)</i>

477
00:30:32,646 --> 00:30:34,816
I want to taste you.

478
00:30:35,819 --> 00:30:37,621
<i>Lancefield: Mm, sweetheart.</i>

479
00:30:37,655 --> 00:30:40,357
Why don't you fish out that
bottle of sherry we've been saving?

480
00:30:40,382 --> 00:30:41,815
Mm.

481
00:30:53,635 --> 00:30:56,272
<i>- Lancefield: You're burning up.
- Am I?</i>

482
00:30:59,209 --> 00:31:01,293
I'd like to know you better.

483
00:31:01,478 --> 00:31:02,838
Oh?

484
00:31:03,746 --> 00:31:06,983
- Is that strange to say?
- No.

485
00:31:07,455 --> 00:31:09,324
Well, I would.

486
00:31:14,228 --> 00:31:15,612
No, well,

487
00:31:16,830 --> 00:31:19,098
I do know you.

488
00:31:21,566 --> 00:31:23,095
I do know you.

489
00:31:24,271 --> 00:31:25,706
I see what you are.

490
00:31:25,740 --> 00:31:28,823
<i>♪ Yokohama just to
teach all those Japs ♪</i>

491
00:31:28,848 --> 00:31:30,514
<i>♪ The Yanks are no saps ♪</i>

492
00:31:30,539 --> 00:31:31,939
<i>♪ A million fightin'
sons of Uncle Sam... ♪</i>

493
00:31:31,964 --> 00:31:36,102
- You can keep a secret.
- Stop it.

494
00:31:36,127 --> 00:31:38,495
I'm just being neighborly.

495
00:31:38,520 --> 00:31:40,221
What are you doing? What are...

496
00:31:40,246 --> 00:31:41,914
Get...

497
00:31:41,939 --> 00:31:44,875
I see what Charlie is doing
and the minute he slips up,

498
00:31:44,900 --> 00:31:47,468
you can be sure I'll be waiting.

499
00:31:53,505 --> 00:31:55,905
<i>-  VoilÃ .
- Mm.</i>

500
00:32:02,959 --> 00:32:05,261
Jesus on a cross...

501
00:32:05,365 --> 00:32:06,932
Absorption rates.

502
00:32:07,217 --> 00:32:09,017
We gotta find Frank right now.

503
00:32:09,052 --> 00:32:11,112
No, no, no. It needs to be
perfect before he sees it.

504
00:32:11,137 --> 00:32:13,049
Double-check the math.

505
00:32:14,222 --> 00:32:15,753
I just didn't know you had it in you.

506
00:32:15,778 --> 00:32:19,012
Honestly, neither did I.

507
00:32:19,259 --> 00:32:21,127
We're gonna need another board.

508
00:32:25,061 --> 00:32:28,431
<i>♪ Good-bye, Mama, I'm
off to Yokohama... ♪</i>

509
00:32:48,245 --> 00:32:50,586
You are persistent.

510
00:32:50,848 --> 00:32:52,685
Persistency

511
00:32:52,806 --> 00:32:55,509
is an overrated quality in a man.

512
00:32:55,888 --> 00:32:57,957
The answer is still no.

513
00:32:57,991 --> 00:33:00,159
I didn't come for your explosives.

514
00:33:00,193 --> 00:33:03,462
Well, I have enough friends, thank you.

515
00:33:03,496 --> 00:33:05,330
I cheated on my wife.

516
00:33:09,644 --> 00:33:12,845
Why you tell me this, huh?

517
00:33:12,870 --> 00:33:15,565
Woman's cousin paid me a friendly visit.

518
00:33:16,246 --> 00:33:18,315
He says he's her cousin.

519
00:33:20,003 --> 00:33:22,005
He wants something.

520
00:33:22,321 --> 00:33:24,519
He left a present on my doorstep.

521
00:33:25,362 --> 00:33:29,129
Well, you have two roads.

522
00:33:29,515 --> 00:33:31,018
One...

523
00:33:33,435 --> 00:33:35,502
you go back home to your wife...

524
00:33:37,821 --> 00:33:39,721
and you tell her everything.

525
00:33:41,276 --> 00:33:43,284
Second road is sounding better.

526
00:33:43,678 --> 00:33:47,046
Well, you visit this cousin,

527
00:33:47,081 --> 00:33:51,156
make sure it's not a friendly visit.

528
00:33:51,181 --> 00:33:53,694
Situations like yours,

529
00:33:54,353 --> 00:33:56,195
they end

530
00:33:56,220 --> 00:34:00,256
in truth or violence.

531
00:34:04,495 --> 00:34:06,363
That's what I'm afraid of.

532
00:34:07,438 --> 00:34:09,090
What would you do?

533
00:34:10,352 --> 00:34:12,286
I'm sorry.

534
00:34:14,772 --> 00:34:17,740
The army counts

535
00:34:17,775 --> 00:34:19,742
its detonators.

536
00:34:21,339 --> 00:34:23,340
I can't loan you any.

537
00:34:25,983 --> 00:34:28,117
But that shotgun...

538
00:34:30,854 --> 00:34:32,554
that's mine.

539
00:35:07,192 --> 00:35:10,726
- (Speaking Spanish)
- He said he asked you for a truck.

540
00:35:12,209 --> 00:35:13,674
I know what he asked for.

541
00:35:14,030 --> 00:35:18,495
- (Speaks Spanish)
- He says, "That isn't a truck."

542
00:35:18,957 --> 00:35:20,793
<i>(Thunder rumbling)</i>

543
00:35:22,937 --> 00:35:24,705
<i>(Engine revs)</i>

544
00:36:17,965 --> 00:36:20,735
- I told him to kill you.
- (Speaks Spanish)

545
00:36:25,807 --> 00:36:28,309
- Are we done?
- (Speaking Spanish)

546
00:36:33,116 --> 00:36:36,817
<i>First, he demands to know what your
army is building on our sacred land.</i>

547
00:36:38,457 --> 00:36:40,853
<i>Then we will be done.</i>

548
00:36:43,123 --> 00:36:45,057
Enjoy your truck.

549
00:36:46,393 --> 00:36:48,630
<i>(Thunder rumbling)</i>

550
00:37:08,756 --> 00:37:10,291
(Whistles)

551
00:37:12,316 --> 00:37:14,050
A little early for a nap.

552
00:37:15,304 --> 00:37:17,261
What the hell is that?

553
00:37:25,420 --> 00:37:29,254
Uh, I don't understand.

554
00:37:29,477 --> 00:37:31,112
There was, uh...

555
00:37:31,423 --> 00:37:34,162
We were looking at absorption rates.

556
00:37:34,187 --> 00:37:37,322
What do absorption rates have
to do with shock wave control?

557
00:37:37,686 --> 00:37:40,214
Or anything else that matters?

558
00:37:40,376 --> 00:37:42,877
I don't remember.

559
00:37:44,132 --> 00:37:45,833
I don't care what the Brits said,

560
00:37:45,967 --> 00:37:47,633
until you're out of my lab,

561
00:37:48,060 --> 00:37:50,897
quit playing hangman on my blackboards.

562
00:38:15,647 --> 00:38:19,316
You know, a cattle rancher
used to own this land.

563
00:38:20,188 --> 00:38:23,320
From here all the way up to the mountains.

564
00:38:23,759 --> 00:38:27,699
But his oldest son, he
liked books, not cows.

565
00:38:27,733 --> 00:38:31,303
So he took off for college,
and when the old man died,

566
00:38:31,338 --> 00:38:33,176
the kid sells it.

567
00:38:33,942 --> 00:38:35,743
You know how much he got?

568
00:38:37,128 --> 00:38:40,928
$300 for all this. Yeah.

569
00:38:41,447 --> 00:38:45,152
Smart men make stupid choices.

570
00:38:46,818 --> 00:38:49,888
Cattle rancher stole it
from the Indians anyway.

571
00:38:49,913 --> 00:38:51,512
Well, if he hadn't,

572
00:38:51,728 --> 00:38:54,563
the two of us would never have met.

573
00:38:55,458 --> 00:38:58,397
You think we would be out
here trying to save the world

574
00:38:58,587 --> 00:39:01,744
on some sacred Indian land?

575
00:39:07,815 --> 00:39:09,215
Thank you.

576
00:39:12,205 --> 00:39:15,452
So how are you gonna
explain this to your wife?

577
00:39:16,189 --> 00:39:18,426
She never liked this car anyway.

578
00:39:18,632 --> 00:39:19,864
Right.

579
00:39:20,417 --> 00:39:22,136
Go easy on the clutch.

580
